external_knowledge:
- 'Passed' refers to test cases that successfully completed without errors;
- 'Average execution time' is calculated by summing the execution times of all test cases in a class and dividing by the number of test cases;
- The overall average execution time is the average of all execution times across all test cases, regardless of class.

- 'Average coverage percentage' refers to the mean percentage of test coverage for each test class;
- 'Number of test results' refers to the count of test results associated with each test class;
- 'No Matching Class' is a placeholder used when there is no corresponding class in the `test_classes` table.

- "blossomed the most" refers to the highest average test coverage;
- "test coverage" is a measure of how much of the code is tested by the test cases;
- "coverage percentage" represents the extent to which the code is covered by tests, typically ranging from 0% to 100%.

- 'Root Class' refers to the topmost class in the hierarchy;
- 'First-Level Child' refers to the immediate child of the root class;
- 'Lower-Level Child' refers to any child class that is not a direct child of the root class;
- 'Blossomed with success' means all test cases in the class passed.

- "heart rate" refers to the overall health and performance of the testing ecosystem;
- The "testing ecosystem" includes all test classes and their dependent cases;
- "how well the tests are performing" is quantified by the average test result, where a result of 'Pass' is considered a positive outcome.

- "root tree" refers to the top-level test case with no dependencies;
- "stands the tallest" refers to the test case with the highest average test coverage;
- "canopy of test coverage" refers to the average coverage percentage of the test case.

- 'bloom times' refers to the average execution time of test cases;
- 'flowers' refers to the test cases themselves;
- 'type of plant' refers to the different types of test cases.

- "test classes" are analogous to different types of flowers in a garden;
- "coverage percentage" refers to the extent to which the test cases cover the code;
- "average execution time" is the mean time taken for all test cases in a class to execute;
- "success rate" is the percentage of test cases that passed out of the total number of test cases in a class.

- "blossomed" refers to the test classes that have performed exceptionally well in terms of test coverage;
- "top 3" indicates the first three results when ranked by average coverage percentage in descending order;
- "last six months" refers to the period from the current date back to six months ago.

- "Test coverage" is a measure of how much of the code is exercised by tests.;
- "Highest average coverage" refers to the test class with the greatest mean percentage of test coverage.;
- "Reigns supreme" is a metaphorical expression indicating the top or best result.
